@mnencia's workaround (`sys.version_info <= (3,0) and os.environ['LANG'] == 'C'`...) is incorrect.
Setting `LANG=C` is, in general, neither sufficient nor necessary to force the C locale.

@kpcyrd, you can't assume that `locale.getpreferredencoding()` returns exactly `'ANSI_X3.4-1968'` when the encoding is ASCII.
For example, on FreeBSD the result is `'US-ASCII'`.

