Ok, I ended up updating the following files (so make sure to use the latest version from the master branch) - [demo](http://jsfiddle.net/Mottie/1a5yu8yq/97/):

* `jquery.tablesorter.js` (core) - only to define `$.tablesorter.dates`
* `parser-date-range.js` - added a new date range format which supports "dd MMMM yyyy"
* `widget-filter-type-insideRange.js` - updated to properly format the filter based on the set language.

Note: if you look at the demo code, you'll see some options that you'll need to include (`globalize` & `filter_searchFiltered`) to allow proper parsing:

```js
var ts = $.tablesorter;

if (!ts.dates) { ts.dates = {}; } // not needed if you update jquery.tablesorter.js

ts.dates.months = $.extend({}, {
    // See http://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/example-widget-grouping.html
    // for details on how to use CLDR data for a locale to add data for this parser
    // CLDR returns an object { 1: "Jan", 2: "Feb", 3: "Mar", ..., 12: "Dec" }
    'it': {
        1: 'Gen',
        2: 'Feb',
        3: 'Mar',
        4: 'Apr',
        5: 'Mag',
        6: 'Giu',
        7: 'Lug',
        8: 'Ago',
        9: 'Set',
        10: 'Ott',
        11: 'Nov',
        12: 'Dic'
    }
}, ts.dates.months);

$(function () {
    var $table = $('table').tablesorter({
        debug: false,
        theme: 'blue',
        widgets: ["zebra", "filter", "numbering"],
        globalize: {
            // set column 0 to use Italian month parser
            0: { lang: 'it' }
        },
        widgetOptions: {
            // filter_anyMatch replaced! Instead use the filter_external option
            // Set to use a jQuery selector (or jQuery object) pointing to the
            // external filter (column specific or any match)
            filter_external: '.search',
            // set to false because it is difficult to determine if a filtered
            // row is already showing when looking at ranges
            filter_searchFiltered: false,
            // include column filters
            filter_columnFilters: true,
            filter_placeholder: {
                search: 'Cerca...'
            },
            filter_saveFilters: true,
            filter_reset: '.reset'
        }
    });

});
```

Hi @theogeels!

For this you'll need to create a custom parser... If the year doesn't matter then I picked an arbitrary year of 2000; no other reason really <img title=":_ drunk :" src="https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/136959/13512352/ab7bd68e-e15f-11e5-8475-64f2678be28e.gif">

Create a parser to flip the month & day, add the arbitrary year and then check if it's a valid date:

```js
$.tablesorter.addParser({
  id: 'dd-mm',
  is: function() {
    return false;
  },
  format: function(str) {
    var date,
      // force dd-mm to use some arbitrary past date so
      // sorting stays consistent
      s = str.split('-').reverse().join('/') + '/2000';
    date = s ? new Date(s) : s;
    return date instanceof Date && isFinite(date) ? date.getTime() : str;
  },
  type: 'numeric'
});
```

Also make sure to include a class name in the header

```html
<th class="sorter-dd-mm">Date</th>
```

Or, include a [`headers` option](https://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#headers) to set the sorter.

Initialize tablesorter and it should work - [demo](https://jsfiddle.net/Mottie/aqt73vz2/)!

Hi @ProgrammingLife!

If you're updating a single cell, then change the `false` to `true` within the "updateCell" trigger ([ref](https://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#updatecell))

```js
// $( "table" ).trigger( "updateCell", [ cell, resort, callback ] );
$( ".table" ).trigger( "updateCell", [ someCell, true ] );
```

If you've updated more than one cell, then either change the resort flag to `true` in the last update, or trigger a new `sorton` ([ref](https://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#sorton)):

```js
var $table = $( ".table" );
var config = $table[0].config;
$table.trigger( "sorton", [ config.sortList ] );
```

@vltr all good points.

Yes, the `exp` will automatically be added to every payload. The one exception is if you make your access tokens non-expirable. **HIGHLY** discouraged since you would effectively have no way to invalidate the token (except maybe changing your secret).

Also, that is certainly one point of the `/auth/verify` endpoint. In a Javascript frontend, I capture the `exp` and then subtract some amount of time to prompt the user to see if they want to keep the session alive. If yes, then go get a refresh token.

```javascript
    checkForTimeout () {
        const {expires} = this.props
        if (expires) {
            const warningNotice = 5
            const warningTime = expires.subtract(warningNotice, 'minutes')
            const secondsToAlert = warningTime.diff(moment())
            setTimeout(() => {
                this.props.notify('warning', {
                    title: "Your session is about to expire",
                    message: `In ${warningNotice} minutes, your session will expire. Do you wish to continue?`,
                    autoDismiss: 0,
                    action: {
                        label: 'Continue',
                        callback: function () {
                            this.props.refreshAccessToken()
                        }.bind(this)
                    }
                })
            }, secondsToAlert)
        }
    }
```

Wrapping all of your calls with `/auth/verify` seems overkill for most web applications. But, then again this is the business logic where EVERY application, whether web based or not, will have different requirements, and therefore need to do something different. Which is why to the extent possible flexibility is the key.

