1) this seems to be a by-product of vectorization, as you can do
```
>>> dy.logistic(dy.inputVector([-100] + [0]*7 + [-100])).npvalue()
array([        nan,  0.49999997,  0.49999997,  0.49999997,  0.49999997,
        0.49999997,  0.49999997,  0.49999997,  0.        ])
```
and the 9th element is not using the vectorized code. Dynet compiles code with "-march=native", which turns on (AVX-something) vectorization in Eigen. A minimal C++ example would be
```
#include <iostream>                                                             
#include <Eigen/Core>                                                           
using namespace Eigen;                                                          
using namespace std;                                                            
Vector4f foo(Vector4f& v)                                                       
{                                                                               
      EIGEN_ASM_COMMENT("begin");                                                 
      Vector4f u = 1.0 / (1.0 + (-v).array().exp());                              
      EIGEN_ASM_COMMENT("end");                                                   
      return u;                                                                   
  }                                                                               
                                                                                  
int main(int argc, char **argv) {                                               
    Vector4f v = {-100, 0, 0, 0};                                               
      cerr << v << endl;                                                          
      Vector4f w = foo(v);                                                        
      cerr << w << endl;                                                          
      exit(0);                                                                    
  }
```
which you can compile with `g++ -I . bla.cc -std=c++11 -march=native -Ofast -o bla` or get the assembly code with `g++ -I . bla.cc -std=c++11 -march=native -Ofast -S` (don't have a mac, so I can't tell what code is generated there).

Tensorflow uses Eigen's internal sigmoid function, which in turn looks exactly like dynet's.

2. A workaround I used in C++ was to use a function like the following (to call before `sgd.update()`):
```
/** returns true if gradients don't show sign of nan-ness
 * otherwise gives some debugging output and returns false
 */
bool check_for_nan(ComputationGraph &hg, Model &model) {
  float result;
  auto p = model.parameters_list()[0];
  p->g_squared_l2norm(&result);
  if (isfinite(result)) {
    return true;
  } else {
    cerr << "Invalid gradient: " << result << endl;
    hg.PrintGraphviz();
    for (auto p: model.parameters_list()) {
      p->clear();
    }
    for (auto p: model.lookup_parameters_list()) {
      p->clear();
    }
    return false;
  }
}
```
(with some code added to PrintGraphviz to output the magnitudes of forward and backward values for each node). This works only if the nan gradient flows to the first parameter, OTOH it can run with negligible overhead. An alternative would be to integrate this with clip_gradients() which normally just aborts with no useful output.

